ts—real people assuming false identities online—and partisan influencers). They use these technologies and strategies to create a bandwagon effect by bringing the content into parallel discussions with other legitimate users, or to mold discontent for political purposes. Drawing on eight years of original international ethnographic research among the people who build, combat, and experience these propaganda campaigns, Woolley presents an extensive view of the evolution of computational propaganda, offers a glimpse into the future, and suggests pragmatic responses for policy makers, academics, technologists, and others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunication in politicsxTechnological innovations. 0aCommunication in politics-Technological innovations. 0aDigital mediaxPolitical aspects. 0aDigital media-Political aspects. 0aDisinformationxTechnological innovations. 0aDisinformation-Technological innovations. 0aPropagandaxTechnological innovations. 0aPropaganda-Technological innovations. 0aSocial mediaxPolitical aspects. 0aSocial media-Political aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Propaganda.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023 Englishz978311131925408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023z9783111318677oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074978640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300269154?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300269154423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97